data.content:
Here are the TUnit equivalents:

```csharp
// Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual);
Assert.That(actual).IsEqualTo(expected);

// Assert.IsTrue(order.IsValid);
Assert.That(order.IsValid).IsTrue();

// Assert.IsNull(result.Error);
Assert.That(result.Error).IsNull();

// Assert.IsInstanceOfType(handler, typeof(IOrderHandler));
Assert.That(handler).IsTypeOf<IOrderHandler>();

// CollectionAssert.Contains(processedIds, 42);
Assert.That(processedIds).Contains(42);

// var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<InvalidOperationException>(() => processor.Run());
var ex = Assert.Throws<InvalidOperationException>(() => processor.Run());

// Assert.AreEqual("Order is empty", ex.Message);
Assert.That(ex.Message).IsEqualTo("Order is empty");
```

**Key differences:**
- TUnit uses a fluent `Assert.That(value).IsX()` pattern
- Collection assertions use the same `Assert.That(...)` entry point
- `ThrowsException<T>` becomes `Throws<T>`
